\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Class 21
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we get into the topics of today's lecture, let's clarify some notation.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring and let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle a\right\rangle =\left\{ ar|r\in R\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle 3\right\rangle =3\mathbb{Z}=\left\{ 3n|n\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For another example, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\mathbb{R}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle x^{2}-2\right\rangle =\left\{ \left(x^{2}-2\right)p\left(x\right)|p\left(x\right)\in\mathbb{R}\left[x\right]\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's show 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is an ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We can use the ideal test! First, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $ar_{1},ar_{2}\in\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ar_{1}-ar_{2}=a\left(r_{1}-r_{2}\right)\in\left\langle a\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ar\in\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(ar\right)s=a\left(rs\right)\in\left\langle a\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is an ideal.
 (Note as 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is commutative, it suffices to show right multiplication absorbs.
 For a non-commutative ring you have to show both sides).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Ring Homomorphisms and Ring Isomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As with groups, we can show some of the structure of rings are preserved
 under homomorphisms and isomorphisms.
 For rings, we have to extend the definition slightly form the definition
 in groups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Def
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be rings.
 A map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:R\rightarrow S$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a+b\right)=\phi\left(a\right)+\phi\left(b\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(ab\right)=\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Ex 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset

 given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(x\right)=_{2}x^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show this is a ring homomorphism, let's first show the addition property
 holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(a+b\right)=_{2}\left(a+b\right)^{2}=_{2}a^{2}+2ab+b^{2}=_{2}a^{2}+b^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
as we are working mod 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $2ab$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(a+b\right)=_{2}a^{2}+b^{2}=_{2}\phi\left(a\right)+\phi\left(b\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, for the multiplication property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(ab\right)=_{2}\left(ab\right)^{2}=_{2}a^{2}b^{2}=_{2}\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Ex 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{R}\left[x\right]\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(p\left(x\right)\right)=p\left(1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the map that takes a polynomial and plugs 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience, we will let 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(x\right)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}p_{i}x^{i},\ q\left(x\right)=\sum_{j=0}^{m}q_{j}x^{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and without loss of generality, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=0,q_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i>n,j>m$
\end_inset

.
 First, let's show the addition property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(p\left(x\right)+q\left(x\right)\right)=\phi\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n}p_{i}x^{i}+\sum_{j=0}^{m}q_{j}x^{j}\right)=\phi\left(\sum_{i=0}^{\max\left\{ n,m\right\} }\left(p_{i}+q_{i}\right)x^{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{i=0}^{\max\left\{ n,m\right\} }\left(p_{i}+q_{i}\right)\left(1\right)^{i}=\sum_{i=0}^{\max\left\{ n,m\right\} }\left(p_{i}+q_{i}\right)\left(1\right)^{i}=\sum_{i=0}^{n}p_{i}\left(1\right)^{i}+\sum_{j=0}^{m}q_{j}\left(1\right)^{j}=\phi\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n}p_{i}x^{i}\right)+\phi\left(\sum_{j=0}^{m}q_{j}x^{j}\right)=\phi\left(p\left(x\right)\right)+\phi\left(q\left(x\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now to show multiplication:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(p\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)\right)=\phi\left(\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n}p_{i}x^{i}\right)\left(\sum_{j=0}^{m}q_{j}x^{j}\right)\right)=\phi\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n+m}\left(\sum_{j=0}^{i}p_{j}q_{i-j}\right)x^{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{i=0}^{n+m}\left(\sum_{j=0}^{i}p_{j}q_{i-j}\right)\left(1\right)^{i}=\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n}p_{i}\left(1\right)^{i}\right)\left(\sum_{j=0}^{m}q_{j}\left(1\right)^{j}\right)=\phi\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n}p_{i}x^{i}\right)\phi\left(\sum_{j=0}^{m}q_{j}x^{j}\right)=\phi\left(p\left(x\right)\right)\phi\left(q\left(x\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Def
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:R\rightarrow S$
\end_inset

 be a ring homomorphism.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is also a bijection, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a ring isomorphism.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R=S$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a ring automorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Non Ex 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{Z}\left[x\right]\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

 given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(p\left(x\right)\right)=-p\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is not a ring isomorphism.
 To show this, we will consider each property: For the addition property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(p\left(x\right)+q\left(x\right)\right)=-\left(p\left(x\right)+q\left(x\right)\right)=-p\left(x\right)-q\left(x\right)=\phi\left(p\left(x\right)\right)+\phi\left(q\left(x\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the multiplication property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(p\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)\right)=-\left(p\left(x\right)q\left(x\right)\right)\neq\left(-p\left(x\right)\right)\left(-q\left(x\right)\right)=\phi\left(p\left(x\right)\right)\phi\left(q\left(x\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the multiplication property will not hold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Ex 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{Q}\left[x\right]\slash\left\langle x^{2}-2\right\rangle \rightarrow\mathbb{Q}\left[\sqrt{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(ax+b\right)=a\sqrt{2}+b
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a ring isomorphism.
 To show this, we can start by showing the addition and multiplication propertie
s:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(\left(ax+b\right)+\left(cx+d\right)\right)=\phi\left(\left(a+c\right)x+\left(b+d\right)\right)=\left(a+c\right)\sqrt{2}+\left(b+d\right)=a\sqrt{2}+b+c\sqrt{2}+d=\phi\left(ax+b\right)+\phi\left(cx+d\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now for the multiplication property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(\left(ax+b\right)\left(cx+d\right)\right)=\phi\left(acx^{2}+\left(a+d\right)x+bd\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But as we have quotiented 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x^{2}-2\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
acx^{2}+\left(a+d\right)x+bd=acx^{2}+\left(a+d\right)x+bd-ac\left(x^{2}-2\right)=\left(a+d\right)x+bd+2ac
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(if we are working in our quotient ring and consider each polynomial as
 a coset representative).
 Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(\left(ax+b\right)\left(cx+d\right)\right)=\phi\left(\left(a+d\right)x+bd+2ac\right)=\left(a+d\right)\sqrt{2}+bd+2ac=\left(a\sqrt{2}+b\right)\left(c\sqrt{2}+d\right)=\phi\left(ax+b\right)\phi\left(cx+d\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let's show we have a bijection.
 For onto, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sqrt{2}+b\in\mathbb{Q}\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(ax+b\right)=a\sqrt{2}+b$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is onto.
 Now, suppose 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(ax+b\right)=\phi\left(cx+d\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\sqrt{2}+b=c\sqrt{2}+d
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a=c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=d$
\end_inset

, so 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ax+b=cx+d
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one.
 As all of the conditions are satisfied, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a ring isomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Properties of Ring Isomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R,S$
\end_inset

 be rings and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:R\rightarrow S$
\end_inset

 be a ring isomorphism.
 Further, let 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Ring Isomorphisms form an equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The composition of ring isomorphisms are a ring isomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(0\right)=0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a ring with unity, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(1\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(-a\right)=-a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a ring with unity and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a^{-1}\right)=\phi\left(a\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a field if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Pf
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Properties 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 will be left as exercises for a future assignment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(0\right)=\phi\left(0+0\right)=\phi\left(0\right)+\phi\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

 from both sides, we get 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\phi\left(0\right)-\phi\left(0\right)=\phi\left(0\right)+\phi\left(0\right)-\phi\left(0\right)=\phi\left(0\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(a\right)=\phi\left(1a\right)=\phi\left(1\right)\phi\left(a\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(1\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\phi\left(0\right)=\phi\left(a-a\right)=\phi\left(a\right)+\phi\left(-a\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so 
\begin_inset Formula $-\phi\left(a\right)=\phi\left(-a\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\phi\left(1\right)=\phi\left(aa^{-1}\right)=\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(a^{-1}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)^{-1}=\phi\left(a^{-1}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
7)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right)=\phi\left(ab\right)=\phi\left(ba\right)=\phi\left(b\right)\phi\left(a\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is onto, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right)=\phi\left(b\right)\phi\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right),\phi\left(b\right)\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Now, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(ab\right)=\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right)=\phi\left(b\right)\phi\left(a\right)=\phi\left(ba\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one, then 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ba$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
8)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists b\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\phi\left(0\right)=\phi\left(ab\right)=\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right),\phi\left(b\right)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor.
 Now, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\phi\left(b\right)\neq0$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(0\right)=0=\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right)=\phi\left(ab\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
but as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one, 
\begin_inset Formula $0=ab$
\end_inset

 and as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right),\phi\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 are both non-zero, then so are 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a zero divisor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
9)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
